            "content": [
              {
                "type": "output_text",
                "text": "Do you mean “secondary agent” in a specific system (customer support, multi-agent AI, robotics, security, etc.), or do you want a general list of possible roles? Here’s a concise, general overview of what a secondary agent can do:\n\n- Monitoring and alerting\n  - Watch system metrics, logs, or user activity and raise alerts or create tickets when anomalies occur.\n\n- Support and escalation\n  - Handle routine queries or tasks and escalate complex issues to a primary agent or human operator.\n\n- Task execution and orchestration\n  - Run subtasks, trigger workflows, or coordinate multiple services on behalf of a primary agent.\n\n- Data processing and enrichment\n  - Clean, transform, aggregate, or annotate data before passing it to the main agent or downstream systems.\n\n- Validation and quality assurance\n  - Verify outputs (e.g., check for correctness, safety, policy compliance) and block or flag unsafe results.\n\n- Safety, access control, and rate limiting\n  - Enforce policies, check permissions, and throttle requests to protect resources.\n\n- Communication bridging\n  - Translate between formats, protocols, languages, or APIs so disparate systems can interoperate.\n\n- Logging, auditing, and provenance\n  - Record actions, decisions, and data lineage for traceability and post‑incident review.\n\n- Specialization and augmentation\n  - Provide domain expertise (e.g., legal, medical) or use specialized models/algorithms to augment the primary agent’s capabilities.\n\n- Fallback and redundancy\n  - Take over limited functionality if the primary agent fails, or provide backup responses.\n\nIf you tell me the context (product, architecture, or workflow), I’ll give a concrete list of capabilities and example implementations tailored to that scenario.",
